    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is grounded in the legal principle that the Constitution is a binding contract between the people and their government, not a living document subject to the whims of modern judges. Proponents argue that this method preserves democratic legitimacy by ensuring that only the elected branches of government, through the amendment process, can alter the fundamental law. By strictly adhering to the text and original public meaning at the time of ratification, originalism prevents unelected judges from imposing their own policy preferences under the guise of constitutional interpretation. This approach maintains the separation of powers and ensures that the Constitution remains a stable, predictable framework for liberty rather than a tool for judicial activism.",
